00:07:25.790 --> 00:07:29.700
All right, so we're not going
far from thermodynamics, we're

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:31.910
going into chemical
equilibrium.

00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:34.710
And we're going to be talking
a lot about delta g.

00:07:34.710 --> 00:07:40.370
So if delta g is not your friend
yet, don't worry, you

00:07:40.370 --> 00:07:45.510
can still bond with delta g.

00:07:45.510 --> 00:07:53.030
All right, so chemical
reactions, chemical reactions

00:07:53.030 --> 00:07:56.910
can go into a state
of equilibrium.

00:07:56.910 --> 00:07:59.700
And it's a dynamic equilibrium,
the reaction is

00:07:59.700 --> 00:08:03.490
still happening, but if a
reaction is an equilibrium,

00:08:03.490 --> 00:08:07.480
the rate of the forward reaction
will equal the rate

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:11.570
of the reverse reaction, so
there'll be no net change in

00:08:11.570 --> 00:08:14.290
composition.

00:08:14.290 --> 00:08:19.310
So let's take a look
at an example.

00:08:19.310 --> 00:08:27.220
So let's look at a reaction in
which we have nitrogen gas,

00:08:27.220 --> 00:08:33.640
and we have hydrogen
gas, and they are

00:08:33.640 --> 00:08:41.450
reacting to form ammonia.

00:08:41.450 --> 00:08:46.650
Suppose we just start with
nitrogen gas and hydrogen gas

00:08:46.650 --> 00:08:49.490
and we don't have any
ammonia left.

00:08:49.490 --> 00:08:56.210
So if we consider concentrations
versus time.

00:08:56.210 --> 00:08:59.290
So say we start with, we have
some nitrogen gas, some

00:08:59.290 --> 00:09:01.580
concentration of nitrogen gas.

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:06.170
As it reacts with hydrogen,
the concentration will

00:09:06.170 --> 00:09:11.970
decrease and then level off.

00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:15.830
We'll start with some amount
of hydrogen gas, and its

00:09:15.830 --> 00:09:22.730
concentration will also decrease
and level off.

00:09:22.730 --> 00:09:25.830
And in the beginning we won't
have any of the product, any

00:09:25.830 --> 00:09:30.510
of the ammonia, so its
concentration will increase

00:09:30.510 --> 00:09:36.230
and then level off.

00:09:36.230 --> 00:09:39.370
So when these reactions level
off, you're reaching

00:09:39.370 --> 00:09:40.070
equilibrium.

00:09:40.070 --> 00:09:42.520
The reaction is still happening,
but the rate of the

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:45.370
forward reaction is equal to
the rate of the reverse

00:09:45.370 --> 00:09:47.680
reaction, so there's
no net change.

00:09:47.680 --> 00:09:51.230
So the concentrations are
staying the same, but there's

00:09:51.230 --> 00:09:56.390
still -- the reaction is
still going forward.

00:09:56.390 --> 00:10:01.290
So let's think about the case
when we have pure reactants

00:10:01.290 --> 00:10:04.470
when we haven't formed enough
products yet to reach

00:10:04.470 --> 00:10:07.050
equilibrium.

00:10:07.050 --> 00:10:15.690
So if we have pure reactants,
the reaction is going to be

00:10:15.690 --> 00:10:19.490
spontaneous in the forward
direction.

00:10:19.490 --> 00:10:25.340
So we'll have a reaction
that is spontaneous

00:10:25.340 --> 00:10:31.010
in the forward direction.

00:10:31.010 --> 00:10:36.590
And what will that mean about
our friend delta g?

00:10:36.590 --> 00:10:42.380
Is it going to be greater
or less than zero?

00:10:42.380 --> 00:10:45.540
So it'll be less than zero --
so delta g or the forward

00:10:45.540 --> 00:10:47.370
reaction will be
less than zero.

00:10:47.370 --> 00:10:50.720
So when delta g is negative, the
reaction is spontaneous in

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:53.020
the forward direction.

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:58.670
So what about when you have
pure products, then the

00:10:58.670 --> 00:11:03.870
reaction should be spontaneous
in the reverse direction.

00:11:03.870 --> 00:11:13.690
So you have spontaneous in the
reverse direction, and what

00:11:13.690 --> 00:11:19.750
does that mean about the
sign of delta g?

00:11:19.750 --> 00:11:22.270
Greater or less than zero?

00:11:22.270 --> 00:11:27.060
Greater, so it'll be positive.

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:31.950
So, we can think about that
in terms of a plot.

00:11:31.950 --> 00:11:39.790
We can think about free
energy versus the

00:11:39.790 --> 00:11:41.840
progress of the reaction.

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:50.145
So, the progress of the
reaction is going this

00:11:50.145 --> 00:11:53.170
direction as you go along.

00:11:53.170 --> 00:12:02.810
So in the beginning if you have
pure reactants, delta g

00:12:02.810 --> 00:12:07.200
is going to be less than zero.

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:11.950
And you're going to proceed
along in the forward direction

00:12:11.950 --> 00:12:14.550
spontaneously.

00:12:14.550 --> 00:12:20.690
If, on the other hand you have
pure products, delta g will be

00:12:20.690 --> 00:12:26.880
positive, so you'll be
spontaneous in the reverse

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:31.880
direction, and the reaction
will go in the reverse

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:38.180
direction until what happens?

00:12:38.180 --> 00:12:41.170
Till you reach equilibrium.

00:12:41.170 --> 00:12:44.810
And what would delta g
be at equilibrium?

00:12:44.810 --> 00:12:49.440
Zero.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:54.530
So you see, there is a great
relationship between delta g

00:12:54.530 --> 00:13:03.830
and equilibrium, so we have
not left delta g behind.

00:13:03.830 --> 00:13:08.230
So, delta g is going to change
as the components of the

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:09.730
reaction change.

00:13:09.730 --> 00:13:13.500
As you have more products or
more reactants, you're going

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:19.250
to have a different delta g.

00:13:19.250 --> 00:13:22.600
So let's look at
some equations.

00:13:22.600 --> 00:13:28.330
So delta g is the change in free
energy, the difference in

00:13:28.330 --> 00:13:32.460
free energy, at some point in
the reaction at any time with

00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:34.100
amount of composition.

00:13:34.100 --> 00:13:37.930
We also have delta g nought,
which talks about delta g

00:13:37.930 --> 00:13:41.360
under particular conditions, so
it's sort of the standard

00:13:41.360 --> 00:13:43.330
free energy.

00:13:43.330 --> 00:13:46.940
We have a term called q, which
is the reaction quotient,

00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:50.420
which tells you about products
and reactants.

00:13:50.420 --> 00:13:54.700
We have our friend r, which is
the gas constant, and this

00:13:54.700 --> 00:13:56.750
depends on temperature.

00:13:56.750 --> 00:14:00.040
So temperature is a term
involved here.

00:14:00.040 --> 00:14:04.350
So the delta g at any point in
the reaction is going to

00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:10.240
depend on the delta g nought
for that reaction, and the

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:12.980
reaction quotient, products
and reactants, and we'll

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:18.390
define this in a minute, and
then the temperature as well.

00:14:18.390 --> 00:14:22.790
So we need to know more about
what q is, what this reaction

00:14:22.790 --> 00:14:25.540
quotient is.

00:14:25.540 --> 00:14:29.760
So this slide looks a little bit
scary, but it's going to

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:33.760
be fine, because a lot of the
terms are going to cancel out.

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:38.140
So we're going to talk about q,
this reaction quotient, and

00:14:38.140 --> 00:14:40.650
we're going to have different
types of problems -- some

00:14:40.650 --> 00:14:42.840
where we're talking about
gases, and others we're

00:14:42.840 --> 00:14:45.510
talking about solutions.

00:14:45.510 --> 00:14:48.780
So you can see two different
kinds of q's, one that depends

00:14:48.780 --> 00:14:51.300
on partial pressure of the gas,
and another that depends

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:52.870
on concentration.

00:14:52.870 --> 00:14:56.520
So here is our equation again
that we just saw -- delta g

00:14:56.520 --> 00:15:00.730
equals delta g nought plus r t
natural log of q, and here

00:15:00.730 --> 00:15:03.590
we've expanded the term for q.

00:15:03.590 --> 00:15:08.070
So p to the sub x is the
partial pressure of a

00:15:08.070 --> 00:15:11.930
particular gas, and so in this
equation, we have a plus b

00:15:11.930 --> 00:15:16.740
going to c plus d, the top of
the line or the products.

00:15:16.740 --> 00:15:19.660
So we have the partial pressure
of gas c, and this is

00:15:19.660 --> 00:15:23.660
over a reference, partial
pressure, raised to the power

00:15:23.660 --> 00:15:28.240
c, the coefficient, and then
also we have d, the partial

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:31.030
pressure of gas d, over a
reference raised to the

00:15:31.030 --> 00:15:32.750
small letter d.

00:15:32.750 --> 00:15:35.890
On the bottom of the terms for
the reactants, partial

00:15:35.890 --> 00:15:38.842
pressure of gas a over a
reference raised to the

00:15:38.842 --> 00:15:42.150
coefficient a, partial pressure
of gas b over the

00:15:42.150 --> 00:15:46.020
reference raised to
the coefficient b.

00:15:46.020 --> 00:15:50.120
Now what's great is that the
partial pressure is one bar,

00:15:50.120 --> 00:15:54.100
and so that basically cancels
out as far as we're concerned.

00:15:54.100 --> 00:15:58.260
And so the term for q
is much simplified.

00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:01.980
You won't see problems that have
the reference in them, so

00:16:01.980 --> 00:16:04.200
you can just think about
q in terms of

00:16:04.200 --> 00:16:06.200
products over reactants.

00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:08.810
And you just have to remember
that the coefficients in the

00:16:08.810 --> 00:16:12.280
reactions do matter.

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:15.110
If you're talking about
