00:37:52.460 --> 00:37:55.450
I need to multiply what?

00:37:55.450 --> 00:37:59.150
Second equation by 2, yeah.

00:37:59.150 --> 00:38:06.870
So to get that to work I would
need to have 2's there, then

00:38:06.870 --> 00:38:11.080
this is going to cancel out and
these will add up, so we

00:38:11.080 --> 00:38:15.630
have 5 and then we have two
of the main products.

00:38:15.630 --> 00:38:20.680
So if I do that, and I have the
equilibrium constant for

00:38:20.680 --> 00:38:24.120
one and for two, how am I
going to get equilibrium

00:38:24.120 --> 00:38:28.970
constant for three?

00:38:28.970 --> 00:38:36.710
I'm going to multiply
k 1 by k 2 and k 2.

00:38:36.710 --> 00:38:40.160
So I'm going to have to multiply
k 2 in there twice,

00:38:40.160 --> 00:38:44.050
because there's two of those
-- we'd multiply that up.

00:38:44.050 --> 00:38:48.460
So if you have different parts
of reactions and you can sum

00:38:48.460 --> 00:38:52.390
them together, then you can
multiply out the individual

00:38:52.390 --> 00:38:55.870
k's to get the new value of k.

00:38:55.870 --> 00:38:59.410
So that's something that's just
useful that you'll run

00:38:59.410 --> 00:39:05.690
into in doing these
types of problems.

00:39:05.690 --> 00:39:07.510
All right.

00:39:07.510 --> 00:39:10.950
Now we're going to
think about how

00:39:10.950 --> 00:39:16.510
equilibriums respond to stress.

00:39:16.510 --> 00:39:19.150
And I always feel like
I need to pause.

00:39:19.150 --> 00:39:24.500
MIT students, you guys are some
of the smartest, most

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:27.160
talented scientists
in the world.

00:39:27.160 --> 00:39:30.090
I don't know if you fully
appreciate how

00:39:30.090 --> 00:39:32.140
smart you all are.

00:39:32.140 --> 00:39:39.300
But this concept is tough
for MIT students.

00:39:39.300 --> 00:39:43.340
So Le Chatelier's principle
says that a system in

00:39:43.340 --> 00:39:49.260
equilibrium that is subjected to
with stress tends to react

00:39:49.260 --> 00:39:57.570
in such a way to minimize
that stress.

00:39:57.570 --> 00:40:00.550
I have advisees coming to
my office saying, "I'm

00:40:00.550 --> 00:40:03.620
double-majoring in this and
that and I'm taking five

00:40:03.620 --> 00:40:07.880
classes and I have UROP and I
have this lab exercise --

00:40:07.880 --> 00:40:10.730
I don't know what's going on,
so I've been thinking a lot

00:40:10.730 --> 00:40:17.160
about it and I think I should
add a third major." Le

00:40:17.160 --> 00:40:20.610
Chatelier would be very
unhappy with that.

00:40:20.610 --> 00:40:25.930
Le Chatelier would say that the
appropriate response is to

00:40:25.930 --> 00:40:33.510
drop one of the majors, to
minimize the stress.

00:40:33.510 --> 00:40:37.160
So in doing these problems, what
I want to encourage you

00:40:37.160 --> 00:40:42.480
to do is think the opposite
of what you would do.

00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:45.900
Minimize the stress.

00:40:45.900 --> 00:40:48.200
If you think about that
you'll be all set.

00:40:48.200 --> 00:40:50.040
All right.

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:55.440
So Le Chatelier's principle
actually is very useful.

00:40:55.440 --> 00:40:59.480
If you think about minimizing
the stress, you'll be able to

00:40:59.480 --> 00:41:04.030
predict the direction that
the reaction will shift.

00:41:04.030 --> 00:41:06.910
So the reaction's going to shift
in a way to minimize the

00:41:06.910 --> 00:41:09.390
stress, so you can predict it.

00:41:09.390 --> 00:41:12.250
If you're thinking along these
lines, you say, oh, that

00:41:12.250 --> 00:41:16.060
system was stressed, and then
you can think about how that

00:41:16.060 --> 00:41:19.370
reaction or that system
is going to respond.

00:41:19.370 --> 00:41:24.380
So let's give some examples.

00:41:24.380 --> 00:41:29.230
So, we have a system in
equilibrium -- we started out,

00:41:29.230 --> 00:41:31.600
we had our nitrogen
and our hydrogen

00:41:31.600 --> 00:41:33.110
and we had no product.

00:41:33.110 --> 00:41:36.080
We reacted the hydrogen and the
nitrogen, their forming

00:41:36.080 --> 00:41:39.800
products, and eventually they
reach equilibrium, their delta

00:41:39.800 --> 00:41:43.510
g equals zero there's still
the reaction going on, but

00:41:43.510 --> 00:41:45.530
there's no net change.

00:41:45.530 --> 00:41:49.990
All right, now the system
is going to be stressed.

00:41:49.990 --> 00:41:54.670
So we're going to add
more of a reactant.

00:41:54.670 --> 00:41:59.720
How will the system react
to minimize that stress?

00:41:59.720 --> 00:42:00.410
What is it going to do?

00:42:00.410 --> 00:42:05.930
It now has too much of
one of the reactants.

00:42:05.930 --> 00:42:09.530
You'll form more products, and
that's going to use up some of

00:42:09.530 --> 00:42:12.505
your other reactant, which will
go down, and you're going

00:42:12.505 --> 00:42:16.940
to form more product until
equilibrium is reached again.

00:42:16.940 --> 00:42:21.050
And one thing that I'll mention
that the ratio has to

00:42:21.050 --> 00:42:21.660
be the same.

00:42:21.660 --> 00:42:25.000
The equilibrium constant is
a constant given the same

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:27.610
temperature, but you're not
necessarily always going to

00:42:27.610 --> 00:42:30.060
have the same concentrations,
but you should have the same

00:42:30.060 --> 00:42:32.710
ratios, the same value of k.

00:42:32.710 --> 00:42:37.200
All right, so what about if you
add more product, what's

00:42:37.200 --> 00:42:40.120
going to happen?

00:42:40.120 --> 00:42:43.940
What direction will the
reaction shift?

00:42:43.940 --> 00:42:47.160
Right, it's going to shift
toward the reactants, so

00:42:47.160 --> 00:42:51.150
you're going to make more of
each of the two reactants

00:42:51.150 --> 00:42:54.920
until again, you find your
equilibrium again.

00:42:54.920 --> 00:42:57.830
And then the reaction's still
going but there's no net

00:42:57.830 --> 00:42:59.490
change anymore.

00:42:59.490 --> 00:43:02.800
All right, so let's think about
this -- let's think

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:05.440
about this in terms of
the math as well.

00:43:05.440 --> 00:43:09.060
If you want to stick with the
math, that's OK, you can think

00:43:09.060 --> 00:43:12.350
about calculating
delta g's here.

00:43:12.350 --> 00:43:14.840
So if you're a system in
equilibrium and you add more

00:43:14.840 --> 00:43:17.490
hydrogen, the system
will respond to

00:43:17.490 --> 00:43:19.390
minimize that increase.

00:43:19.390 --> 00:43:23.490
So it's going to make more
product that will minimize the

00:43:23.490 --> 00:43:26.930
increase, it shifts
to the right.

00:43:26.930 --> 00:43:31.390
And this can be explained
in terms of q and k.

00:43:31.390 --> 00:43:34.150
So, you can think about,
again, do you have more

00:43:34.150 --> 00:43:39.130
products now or did you have
more products at equilibrium,

00:43:39.130 --> 00:43:43.990
and if you're adding more
reactants, momentarily q will

00:43:43.990 --> 00:43:47.740
become less than k.

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:52.260
And so, you would get a negative
delta g, which would

00:43:52.260 --> 00:43:56.640
make it spontaneous in the
forward direction.

00:43:56.640 --> 00:44:00.210
So some people like to think
about this in terms of delta g

00:44:00.210 --> 00:44:03.100
equals r t natural
log of q over k.

00:44:03.100 --> 00:44:08.040
So you think about if q is less
than k, what sign you

00:44:08.040 --> 00:44:10.780
have for delta g, and that's
tells you whether the reaction

00:44:10.780 --> 00:44:14.310
is spontaneous in the forward
or the reverse direction.

00:44:14.310 --> 00:44:17.030
And let me just give you
one hint for taking

00:44:17.030 --> 00:44:19.380
exams in this unit.

00:44:19.380 --> 00:44:23.340
That use of the arrow is really
good, or saying "toward

00:44:23.340 --> 00:44:26.440
product" or "reactant." I can't
tell you how many people

00:44:26.440 --> 00:44:29.500
write -- know what the answer
is and write left when mean

00:44:29.500 --> 00:44:32.350
right, or write right
when they mean left.

00:44:32.350 --> 00:44:36.350
But if you draw an arrow you
never really get it wrong, and

00:44:36.350 --> 00:44:39.640
when you say products or
reactants it's a lot harder to

00:44:39.640 --> 00:44:41.610
make that mistake.

00:44:41.610 --> 00:44:44.610
So if you're not good with right
or left, which let me

00:44:44.610 --> 00:44:48.040
tell you a large fraction of
people are not, hedge your

00:44:48.040 --> 00:44:49.950
bets, you can write everything,
more products,

00:44:49.950 --> 00:44:53.100
arrows, and then write if you
want, then you're pretty sure

00:44:53.100 --> 00:44:55.930
that you have it all in there.

00:44:55.930 --> 00:44:56.810
OK.

00:44:56.810 --> 00:45:03.050
So again, we can explain this
in terms of q or k.

00:45:03.050 --> 00:45:04.990
All right.

00:45:04.990 --> 00:45:08.880
So let's just quickly talk about
adding more products.

00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:10.040
